   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="transcription">
            <fw type="leafNum" corresp="#lf">119</fw>
            <p>
<lb corresp="#b2"/><w>ywawont</w><w>koṃ</w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">matured day</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment"><bibl><title corresp="ref:maue2010"/><citedRange>345</citedRange></bibl> reads <hi>ywawon<hi rend="underline">t</hi><hi rend="subscript">\</hi> ko</hi> and identifies the gloss as TA, remarking that <hi>-ont</hi> is found "bei Adjektiven des Typs parno und PP des Typs kälpo" ["with adjectives of the parno-type and with PPs of the kälpo-type"]. Indeed, <hi>ywawont</hi> is probably a preterite participle of the verb <hi>yäwā-</hi> 'turn towards', also used in the sense 'ripen' (<bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2010"/><citedRange>805-7</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>799</citedRange></bibl>). Apparently the present stem <hi>ywa-</hi> was reintroduced into the pt.ptc. of this verb, which regularly is <hi>ywo</hi>, obl.sg.masc. <hi>ywont</hi>. Whether <hi>vikāla°</hi> is to be taken as 'zur Unzeit' ['at an inopportune time'] (cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:sanderandwaldschmidt1985"/><citedRange>155</citedRange></bibl>) or simply as 'in the twighlight; in the evening' remains to be seen.</note><note type="philcomment">Glosses Skt. <hi>vikāla°</hi> 'twilight, evening, afternoon'.</note></p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography">
            <p><label>Online access</label><bibl><title corresp="ref:idp0000"/><ref target="http://idp.bbaw.de/database/oo_loader.a4d?pm=SHT 1157" type="external">SHT 1157</ref></bibl>. </p>
            <p><label>other</label><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2014"/><citedRange>133, 150</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:maue2010"/><citedRange>345</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
         </div>
